The paper discusses the security of a modern Single Sign-On authentication protocol, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the use of federated identity management and authentication, which is related to the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also analyzes the protocol's features and extensions, which falls under the category of software engineering (cs.SE). The paper also discusses the potential security vulnerabilities and attacks, which is related to the sub-category of cybercrime (cs.CY). Finally, the paper proposes countermeasures to fix the issues, which falls under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC).
